The paper discusses a model for social and information networks that takes into account node attributes, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The paper also analyzes the mathematical properties of the model, which could place it in the sub-category of Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) or Learning (cs.LG). The study of network patterns and emergence could also suggest the sub-category of Social Computing (cs.SOC). Finally, the analysis of degree distributions could place it in the sub-category of Statistical Learning (cs.SD).
